Blocks.childText: THE PRAISE OF FAITH. 65 DUKE STREET. L.M. J. HATTON. 'T is by the faith of joys to come, We walk thro' deserts dark as night; Till we arrive at heav'n, our home, Faith is our guide, and faith our light. 5.02 169 Heb. 11: 8. I. WATTS. 170 Titus 2: 10. I. WATTS. 1 'Tis by the faith of joys to come, 1 So let our lips and lives express We walk through deserts dark as night; The holy gospel we profess; Till we arrive at heaven, our home, So let our works and virtues shine, Faith is our guide, and faith our light. To prove the doctrine all divine. 2 The want of sight she well supplies; 2 Thus shall we best proclaim abroad She makes the pearly gates appear; The honors of our Saviour God; Far into distant worlds she pries, When His salvation reigns within, And brings eternal glories near. And grace subdues the power of sin. 3 Cheerful we tread the desert through, 3 Religion bears our spirits up, While faith inspires a heavenly ray; While we expect the blessed hope,- Though lions roar, and tempests blow, The bright appearance of the Lord: And rocks and dangers fill the way. And faith stands leaning on His word. 171 Luke 11: 2. C. ELLIOTT. 1 My God, my Father, while I stray 4 If but my fainting heart be blest Far from my home, on life's rough way, With Thy sweet Spirit for its guest, Oh, teach me from my heart to say, My God, to Thee I leave the rest; "Thy will be done, Thy will be done!" "Thy will be done, Thy will be done!" 2 What though in lonely grief I sigh 5 Renew my will from day to day; For friends beloved no longer nigh; Blend it with Thine, and take away Submissive still would I reply, Whate'er now makes it hard to say, "Thy will be done, Thy will be done!" Thy will be done, Thy will be done!" 3 If Thou shouldst call me to resign 6 Then when on earth I breathe no more What most I prize,- it ne'er was mine; The prayer oft mixed with tears before, I only yield Thee what was Thine: I'll sing, upon a happier shore, "Thy will be done, Thy will be done!" 'Thy will be done, Thy will be done."
